18:T41d,I know I am no expert. As much as I wanted to go to higher education for creative writing I went down the criminal justice path instead. There are thousands of people online (and in person conferences) who will tell you where to start or how to go about world building. Remember, one size does not fit all when it comes to fiction. My go to is Pinterest. I will search world building there and I usually take from multiple sources to find questions to help aide in the process of world building. I also know that Brandon Sanderson has posted lectures on YouTube, and I'm sure there are loads of TedTalks or other podcasts which talk about it. Just search up World Building or Fictional World Building and I'm sure you'll find much deeper explanations. My purpose here was simply to help you realize that your story is so much more than the characters you name or the cities you name. You are a creator in your own right. You have so much more to consider than you realize. And enjoy the process! This is what makes writing enjoyable--create your escape.19:T47f,I only started learning about tropes in the last 18 months. I wish I had started researching them sooner!! It would have helped the writing process so much. I didn't realize there were tropes which were expected in certain genres. And I didn't realize how many tropes were so despised. For those of you who don't know (like I didn't) tropes are basically cliches. That thing that's similar across books? They're usually short descriptors. Some of my personal favorites (to read) are the mentor and chosen one, the enemies to lovers, medieval settings, and the quest. These seem like obvious factors into things and usually they are, but some others can be more obscure like magic with a price, haunted landscapes (or local ghost stories), redeemed villains, or the retired heroes. Once you understand what a trope is, it's easier to work it into your story planning. I know for my next project I'm going to make a list of tropes I want to include and find ways to incorporate them. (Pro tip - it also makes marketing so much easier. And pitching to agents. And knowing how to publish your book. Just research tropes and find which ones fit your book.)6:["$","div",null,{"className":"pt-24 pb-24","children":[["$","$L16",null,{}],["$","div",null,{"className":"container mb-16","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none","children":["$","h1",null,{"children":"Posts"}]}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"container mb-8","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"font-semibold","children":[false,"Showing 1 - 6 of 6 Posts"]}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"container","children":["$","div",null,{"children":["$","div",null,{"className":"grid grid-cols-4 sm:grid-cols-8 lg:grid-cols-12 gap-y-4 gap-x-4 lg:gap-y-8 lg:gap-x-8 xl:gap-x-8","children":[["$","div","0",{"className":"col-span-4","children":["$","$L17",null,{"className":"h-full","doc":{"id":15,"title":"Where Do I Start?","content":{"root":{"children":[{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I had a friend ask me this weekend where he should start. He has an amazing idea for a book but no idea what to do with it. I realized I had never actually thought about it like that. I don't even remember where I started, I just know where I'm at. I thought it was worth it to write a blog post with the information I told him.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I have an idea. Now what?","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h3"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"My friend said his idea was a postapocalyptic story. I have no experience with this so I tried to equate it to my process with fantasy writing. Hopefully it will be applicable to everyone.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Forgive my metaphor but it is the one I used when talking with my friend. God built a world before he created man. World building should be your step one. You can't have a story without characters and you can't have characters without a place for them to live. What are the requirements for survival? Shelter, then water, then food. Give your characters shelter.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"World Building","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h2"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"We'll start here. Now, world building is so much more than just a world. It's a climate, sure. It's landscape. But it's also history. It's society. It's culture. It's religion.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I want you to imagine a ball of clay. Look at this ball of blue clay in your hand. You can mold it and shape it into anything. You are the creator. There are some rules of course. If you want more colors you need to add something to the blue clay to either change the color or to add other clay of a different color. You probably shouldn't eat it, but I can't tell you how to manage your gut health. You get the point. There are laws of physics, but when you're writing a story it's important to remember some rules are made to be broken--responsibly and stylistically of course.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"When deciding on your world, I want you to think about the type of story you want to write. Lets go back to the postapocalyptic story idea. I'm assuming you'll still be on earth. Your globe is already formed, your solar system, your laws of physics. They're already in place. So look deeper. How far after the apocalypse is it? What did the apocalypse look like in your story? What still exists, what has been made moot?  Is there any kind of technology that still works, or has your world gone Y2K and all electricity is gone? Forget about the people for now. Just focus on what the world looks like. What does the wildlife look like? Plants, animals, pollution?","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Once you can fully visualize this world, what problems exist on it? Are there monsters roaming the lands? Are there cults or gangs that are fighting for power? What does power look like? Is it money? Resources? When the world ended, what was left?","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I am going to place my hypothetical world a few years after the end of the world so my peoples are all established well enough. There have to be new rules of society. Is there a barter system in place or is it a free for all? Is there some sort of currency? Are the people nomads or do they band together for survival in numbers?","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"If you start broad (say a solar system) and then work your way down (solar system, star, planet, continents, countries, cities, townships, streets, houses, family, individual) you'll be able to get a better feel for what your character's motivations are.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Culture Building","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h2"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Now that you have a physical shelter for your character focus next on their surrounding culture. What are the components of culture? According to a quick Google search it is:","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Values and Beliefs","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":2,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Norms","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":2,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Symbols","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":2,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Language","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":2,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Rituals","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":2,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Social Structure","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":2,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Economy","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":2,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Some of these concepts may not be applicable to your story. That's okay. It's better to be over prepared than under. I read one author talk about a \"parking garage\". While she is editing her books she will take unnecessary information from the book and instead of deleting it she parked it in a \"garage\" or a document for lost parts. Come back to it later. It may be necessary further down the road or might even make for nice bonus material. If anyone else remembers the original \"Pottermore\" it was where JKR put a lot of her bonus material. You could wander Hogwarts and select certain objects and receive insider knowledge about them or the story. There are so many options for how you can use this \"extra\" information. But you need to know it. You need to know how it affects your characters. You need to know how it affects your story.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"A Word on History","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h2"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I'm not telling you to write a history book for your novel. I'm not ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"not","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" telling you to write a history book for your novel. What I'm telling you is history matters. I live in America. History is every bit a part of me as it is a historian. I'm a member of a religion which focuses a lot on heritage. I know stories from several generations back, from grandparents I never met. I know the history of my religion. I know (generally) the history of my country. I know the history of several wars (or at least the history the victors write, which is another thing altogether). When I say history I don't mean your character has to have conversations about it. I don't know the last time I talked about WWI. I don't know the last time I talked about Thomas Edison or even Shakespeare. But I know history. Your character will, too, whether it's necessary to their day or not.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"But my book has nothing to do with religion.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h2"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Look. I thought this, too. When I first started writing ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Pulchra","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" I had no religion involved in it whatsoever. Now the published version? Magic comes from the gods. Trust me when I say that completely took me by surprise when I was rewriting the book. It happens. In ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"My World of Glass","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" my character Sabrina is very devote worshiper. She's a side character. Her religion isn't really talked about. I couldn't even tell you what church she belongs to. But religion makes stories richer because it makes them more real. Your character may be agnostic. But how does the rest of the world handle death? And if the world is agnostic, what do they do with the bodies of their dead? Religion affects a lot more than just what god does someone believe in. It usually has a hand in society morals or traditions somewhere along the line.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Don't take my word for it.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h2"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"$18","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"World Building Like Mandy","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h2"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I have considered making my own lecture and possibly recording it and putting it online or making supplemental guides. This is something I really enjoy, so let me know if you are interested and I can work on that!","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"root","version":1}},"relatedPosts":[{"id":9,"title":"What's a Pantser? Where do I begin?","categories":[8,7,10,9],"meta":{"image":25,"description":"Pantser? Planner? Plantser? What are these terms and how do they relate to starting a fictional novel? In this post I talk about my general process."},"slug":"whats-a-pantser-where-do-i-begin"},{"id":14,"title":"10 Things I Wish I Knew Sooner","categories":[9,7,8],"meta":{"image":27,"description":"I read these kinds of posts ALL the time. But I realized the articles said stuff I knew. So I compiled the things I wish I could tell younger Me."},"slug":"10-things-i-wish-i-knew-sooner"}],"categories":[{"id":8,"title":"Writing Process","parent":null,"breadcrumbs":[{"id":"679261f40c90a70a5c272165","doc":8,"url":null,"label":"Writing Process"}],"updatedAt":"2025-01-23T15:36:20.511Z","createdAt":"2025-01-23T15:36:20.489Z"},{"id":9,"title":"Resources","parent":null,"breadcrumbs":[{"id":"679261ff0c90a70a5c272167","doc":9,"url":null,"label":"Resources"}],"updatedAt":"2025-01-23T15:36:31.770Z","createdAt":"2025-01-23T15:36:31.752Z"},{"id":7,"title":"Behind the Scenes","parent":null,"breadcrumbs":[{"id":"67913df2d94eaa4a0d933d6d","doc":7,"url":null,"label":"Behind the Scenes"}],"updatedAt":"2025-01-22T18:50:26.922Z","createdAt":"2025-01-22T18:50:26.894Z"}],"meta":{"title":"Where should I start when writing my book I've planned?","image":{"id":28,"alt":"Photo by Greg Rakozy on Unsplash of a sillhouette standing beneath a starry sky","caption":null,"updatedAt":"2025-04-22T15:38:24.090Z","createdAt":"2025-04-22T15:38:24.090Z","url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/greg-rakozy-oMpAz-DN-9I-unsplash (1).jpg","thumbnailURL":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/greg-rakozy-oMpAz-DN-9I-unsplash (1)-300x200.jpg","filename":"greg-rakozy-oMpAz-DN-9I-unsplash (1).jpg","mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":56316,"width":640,"height":427,"focalX":50,"focalY":50,"sizes":{"thumbnail":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/greg-rakozy-oMpAz-DN-9I-unsplash (1)-300x200.jpg","width":300,"height":200,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":11428,"filename":"greg-rakozy-oMpAz-DN-9I-unsplash (1)-300x200.jpg"},"square":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/greg-rakozy-oMpAz-DN-9I-unsplash (1)-500x500.jpg","width":500,"height":500,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":51761,"filename":"greg-rakozy-oMpAz-DN-9I-unsplash (1)-500x500.jpg"},"small":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/greg-rakozy-oMpAz-DN-9I-unsplash (1)-600x400.jpg","width":600,"height":400,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":46598,"filename":"greg-rakozy-oMpAz-DN-9I-unsplash (1)-600x400.jpg"},"medium":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/greg-rakozy-oMpAz-DN-9I-unsplash (1)-900x600.jpg","width":900,"height":600,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":84161,"filename":"greg-rakozy-oMpAz-DN-9I-unsplash (1)-900x600.jpg"},"large":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/greg-rakozy-oMpAz-DN-9I-unsplash (1)-1400x934.jpg","width":1400,"height":934,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":156142,"filename":"greg-rakozy-oMpAz-DN-9I-unsplash (1)-1400x934.jpg"},"xlarge":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/greg-rakozy-oMpAz-DN-9I-unsplash (1)-1920x1281.jpg","width":1920,"height":1281,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":232657,"filename":"greg-rakozy-oMpAz-DN-9I-unsplash (1)-1920x1281.jpg"}}},"description":"I was asked where he should start with his book. I realized I don't remember where I started. I thought it was worth it to write what I told him."},"publishedAt":"2025-04-22T15:40:00.000Z","authors":[3],"populatedAuthors":[{"id":3,"name":"Mandy"}],"slug":"where-do-i-start","slugLock":true,"updatedAt":"2025-04-22T15:48:24.191Z","createdAt":"2025-04-22T14:55:40.040Z","_status":"published"},"relationTo":"posts","showCategories":true}]}],["$","div","1",{"className":"col-span-4","children":["$","$L17",null,{"className":"h-full","doc":{"id":14,"title":"10 Things I Wish I Knew Sooner","content":{"root":{"children":[{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I read these kinds of posts ALL the time because I feel like I don't have enough knowledge or experience to be an expert. But recently (like within the last 5 years or so) I was realizing all of the articles said the same stuff and it's all stuff I knew. So I wanted to compile a list of the things I wish I could tell younger Me about writing.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[],"direction":null,"format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"10 Things I Wish I Knew Before","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h1"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"1. The Pen Really is Better","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h3"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"When I first started writing I insisted on using pencils so I could erase my mistakes. Then, I saw a friend who had the same mindset as me and his notebook was completely smudged. I mean full pages just gray with graphite and no legible words. It freaked me out and I convinced my parents to let me use the computer every day (after homework of course) to type up what I had written for my book that day. I wish I could go back to 12 year old me and sit her down with some honesty. The whole point of the pencil was to be able to change things. Then with the computer I could use the backspace and delete buttons to my heart's content. I wish I could go back and tell little me to change to pens. Eventually I learned to ignore the backspace button but it took a long time. I know I wouldn't be so perfectionist on my work if I had learned that lesson earlier. Your first draft is for the mistakes. It's supposed to be messy and incorrect. It's SUPPOSED to be word vomit!","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"type":"linebreak","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"2. “ASPIRING” Isn’t An Option","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h3"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I see this phrase EVERYWHERE on author social media. “Hi, I’m Jane Doe and I’m an Aspiring Author”. No. You’re freaking THE Jane Doe, author. Period. The only aspiring authors are the ones who haven’t put anything on paper (or computer) yet. If you keep this mindset of \"I'm aspiring because I'm not published\" you're in for a lot of heartbreak and imposter syndrome. Do you know how many people on this PLANET want to write a book? I don't either, but based on the people who have told me that I'm sure it's a large majority. If you are putting words to paper (or computer!) with the intention of it being some sort of book, you are an author. I dare you to look up the definition of AUTHOR and point to where it says PUBLISHED.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"*Caveat to that: if you're looking to be an author full time, the likelihood of ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"that","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" goal can be aspired to. But you are NOT an aspiring author. You are an author with a goal to one day be a full time creator.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"type":"linebreak","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"3. Social Media is NECESSARY","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h3"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Publishing your book goes WAY beyond signing on the dotted line. You need to market and the most viable way to market is through social media. I wish I had started learning earlier what that meant so I could learn. I feel so behind now. Social media is difficult for me. I don't know what to say, or how to say it. I'm a natural introvert (as I'm sure a lot of writers are) so interacting with strangers online is sometimes more torturous than mutilation. It's really really hard for me. I've been trying to learn (and enlisting social media managers who can teach me). I do not subscribe to the idea, however, of buying expensive courses from \"social media influencers\". Not even the ones directed at authors. (And don't even get me started on the unpublished authors who have courses on how to get published. Puh-LEASE.) But I am trying to learn, because that's where the readers are now.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"type":"linebreak","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"4. Even Realistic Fiction Needs Research","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h3"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I used to think my fiction books didn’t require any research whatsoever because they were coming from a world in my head. I have never planned out what needed to be researched. But even in My World of Glass I researched Chicago, laws, government historical cycles, and so many other things. I'm constantly researching. I can't write without Google being pulled up next to me. I want to go back and slap little 17 year old me silly for being so arrogant. Research, even for the most magical fantasy, is so very important. If you don't know how to research, I suggest you learn.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"type":"linebreak","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"5. Anything is Possible","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h3"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"You might get that contract with a Big 5 publisher, you might self publish. You might become a best seller, you might not. Every path is different and that’s OKAY. I know so many authors who have published with big shot publishers and are not known to the general public. I know lots of authors who have self published and have made it to being full time creators. Every path is going to be different and it's going to be whatever path you make it.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"type":"linebreak","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"6. The Muse is Real","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h3"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I never understood what the muses really are. Had I known, I wouldn’t have gone years without writers block not putting a single word down. For me, my muse is my readers. If I have a reader I'm spoon feeding to, I have motivation. If I have a passive reader, I lose steam. I can try to supplement with music or reading or movies, but that doesn't last long. It's like a shot of adrenaline. It's great while it lasts but when it fades off I'm in an energy slump for a bit. the most consistent method for me to write is to share my writing with a trusted reader who can tell me \"That didn't make sense\" or \"Ohmygosh I love this character\". Everyone needs to find their own muse. Lots of writers keep their works very private until they feel it's completed (which isn't for me because I NEVER feel like my work is completed) and that's okay too, as long as they know who their muse is.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"type":"linebreak","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"7. You Can’t Please Everyone","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h3"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"This one is a hard pill to swallow. My muse (see above) is my readers. Had I known this earlier I wouldn’t have hidden my work away like I did, like I saw other people doing. But once I started sharing more consistently I needed to understand my books aren’t for everyone. And that’s okay because I can’t stand some popular books right now. \"This is a very subjective field\" as so many agents have told me over the last year.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"type":"linebreak","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"8. It’s a Long Process","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h3"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Breathe. I can whip out 50,000 words in a month and get a first draft on paper without breaking a sweat. But it’ll be years before that book is ready to be published and lots of hard work. (Please don’t go find my Rose Winters books — those were published as second drafts and I regret it so much) I thought my writing was top notch (because all my English teachers loved me, obviously) but it wasn't until I started getting real editors and professional readers looking through my books to realize that I actually leave a lot in my head that I forget to put on paper. And because it's in my head, I don't realize my readers are missing important details. Get the second opinion. And the third, the fourth, the fifth. And make them unbiased parties, I beg of you. Allow your sensitive skin to be jabbed at a bit. Do your story justice.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"type":"linebreak","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"9. TROPES","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h3"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"$19","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[],"direction":null,"format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"10. There's No One Size Fits All","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h3"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Like I mentioned before this list, I used to read these lists all the time. I would spend hours researching author's processes and what they did to find success. Which is great, truly. It gives you an \"insider's look\" in this field. But realize that you can pick and choose. If something doesn't work for you in this list, I am not going to be offended if you pretend I never said it. Just like how not every book fits every reader, every writing trick will not work for every writer. Being a creator means there are some guidelines to keep you within a standard so people can enjoy your work while enjoying others', but some rules are made to be broken. Just make sure you know which rules are made to be broken, and which broken rules will discredit your work.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[],"direction":null,"format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I know nobody asked for my opinion on this. But I wanted to share what I've learned over the last 15 years of serious writing. Because I have learned a lot, and I don't care to be silenced by louder voices. Take what I say with a grain of salt, but take it nonetheless. Let me know if any of these points leave you with burning questions. I'm happy to share my experience with you.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"root","version":1}},"relatedPosts":[],"categories":["$6:props:children:3:props:children:props:children:props:children:0:props:children:props:doc:categories:1","$6:props:children:3:props:children:props:children:props:children:0:props:children:props:doc:categories:2","$6:props:children:3:props:children:props:children:props:children:0:props:children:props:doc:categories:0"],"meta":{"title":"10 Things I Wish I Knew Sooner -- Writing Edition!","image":{"id":27,"alt":"Image of decaying greek building with statues of women holding up the ceiling","caption":{"root":{"children":[{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Photo by Hoàng Vũ ","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"root","version":1}},"updatedAt":"2025-03-13T15:41:44.525Z","createdAt":"2025-03-13T15:41:44.525Z","url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/greek statues.jpg","thumbnailURL":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/greek statues-300x450.jpg","filename":"greek statues.jpg","mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":65153,"width":640,"height":960,"focalX":50,"focalY":50,"sizes":{"thumbnail":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/greek statues-300x450.jpg","width":300,"height":450,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":20443,"filename":"greek statues-300x450.jpg"},"square":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/greek statues-500x500.jpg","width":500,"height":500,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":32765,"filename":"greek statues-500x500.jpg"},"small":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/greek statues-600x900.jpg","width":600,"height":900,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":64313,"filename":"greek statues-600x900.jpg"},"medium":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/greek statues-900x1350.jpg","width":900,"height":1350,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":115493,"filename":"greek statues-900x1350.jpg"},"large":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/greek statues-1400x2100.jpg","width":1400,"height":2100,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":214727,"filename":"greek statues-1400x2100.jpg"},"xlarge":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/greek statues-1920x2880.jpg","width":1920,"height":2880,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":313906,"filename":"greek statues-1920x2880.jpg"}}},"description":"I read these kinds of posts ALL the time. But I realized the articles said stuff I knew. So I compiled the things I wish I could tell younger Me."},"publishedAt":"2025-03-13T16:00:00.000Z","authors":[3],"populatedAuthors":[{"id":3,"name":"Mandy"}],"slug":"10-things-i-wish-i-knew-sooner","slugLock":true,"updatedAt":"2025-03-13T15:44:18.928Z","createdAt":"2025-03-13T14:50:01.492Z","_status":"published"},"relationTo":"posts","showCategories":true}]}],["$","div","2",{"className":"col-span-4","children":["$","$L17",null,{"className":"h-full","doc":{"id":11,"title":"Inspiration Behind PULCHRA ARCANUM","content":{"root":{"children":[{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Pulchra Arcanum","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h1"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Setting the Scene","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h3"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"It's September 2018. I had just been married at the first of the month and have a countdown to November 1 when National Novel Writing Month begins. I have been participating for almost 10 years and this is the first year my brand new husband gets a front row seat to my insanity.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I'm sitting in my chair at work during a really slow moment in the bank. I have an internet browser pulled up and I am perusing the forums on the nanowrimo (National Novel Writing Month) website. (","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"*author note: nanowrimo was a nonprofit program designed to help writers write 50,000 words in a 30 day period. It started in 1999 as a challenge between friends and quickly became an international tradition. After a scandal in 2022/2023 time frame the nonprofit went downhill quickly and the final year was 2024. I personally stopped after the 2023 drama unfolded.)","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" I know that I want to win the challenge this year and in order to do that I need a really tantalizing story idea. But I'm drawing a blank.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Inspiration Strikes!","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h3"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I want to try something new. I want something that will require me to do some research and stretch myself a bit. I play with the idea of a gypsy/Romani story idea but that was struck down by people in the forums as being culturally poor in taste. So I decided to keep looking. At the time I was re-watching the BBC show ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Merlin ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"and decided ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"voila","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"! Here was a great idea. Something to do with King Arthur and his friend Merlin.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"But this is such an over told story! How can I make it unique?","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"In all of the depictions I had ever seen or read (which was admittedly a very small handful of options), Merlin and Arthur were these amazing characters who had so much going for them and everyone loved them. So what if they weren't?","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I love the BBC depiction of Morgan le Fey. She's so pretty and her character is so rich with growth. I wanted to write about her. And somewhere in my research I found a prompt to write a story from the villain's perspective. Win-win!","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Step One: Main Character","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h3"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I did very little research into the myth of Camelot. Embarrassingly little. I jumped head first into character development. I didn't want to use the name Morgan (mostly because it was on my list of names for a potential child one day and I had promised myself I would never use a name of a character I wrote for one of my children) so I had to come up with something else.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I went to my trusty name website (","type":"text","version":1},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"behindthename.com","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"link","version":3,"fields":{"url":"https://www.behindthename.com/","newTab":true,"linkType":"custom"},"id":"6807bdbea1560bbe05c0778c"},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":") and started doing some searches for names. I had several that fit the general vibe I wanted and put it up to a poll with my friends. I landed on Megara with a nickname of Meggy. And I started character design.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I knew I wanted her to be blond. There are so many brunette characters in fiction. And especially since the original concept was writing from a villain's point of view it felt right to have a blonde villain. I thought it was clever, okay?","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Step Two: Conflict","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h3"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"What made Meggy a villain? Why was she evil? Why am I writing a story from her perspective? What is her ambition? These are the questions I asked myself. I like the saying \"there's two sides to every story\" and that was the tagline to ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Pulchra","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" for a very long time. So I decided to look at it from Merlin's point of view. What did he see in Meggy that made her a villain? The best thing I could come up with was jealousy. Why would Merlin, a magical sorcerer, be jealous of a young girl?","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"He has no magic, of course.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"But if he has no magic, how does he play into King Arthur's life? Where does Excalibur come into play?","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Meggy has Merlin's magic. And he is angry about it.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Step Three: Allies","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h3"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"So I know Meggy is my main character (who is seeming less and less like a villain, but that's fine) but who else is in her life? Well, every witch needs a familiar. So that began the search to find an animal sidekick. I looked up the natural wildlife for the UK (because where else would Camelot be?) and came up with a list of options to present to my friends. And I'm talking options. At one point, I considered a deer of some kind. My friends and I finally landed on a stoat. Those buggers are cute! Again, very little research went into this decision. Most of my research for stoats didn't happen until book two. I'm really terrible with research.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Now that my animal type was picked out? What would his name be?","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I wanted Meggy to name him. That much was clear. By now I knew she spent most of her life in hiding (thanks, Merlin) so she would be very sheltered. And she's very book smart. How would she describe this creature? I thought about what he might look like and what she might know. And, admittedly, his first name was not the most realistic for that question. The stoat was originally named ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Luter Terram","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" (or, Latin for Land Otter). Before publishing it got changed to ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Superus","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" which is Latin for Otherworldly. It fit better.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Now, who were her human allies?","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I wanted the book to be written in two perspectives. And I wanted the second perspective to be from a man who understood the world better than her and who would love her for who she was, villain and all. I have a type, and I wanted to be attracted to my own character. Five years later some reel on Instagram would point out that I married my main character (by traits, not appearance. I actually would not be attracted to Leo's physical appearance in the least. He's designed to be conventionally attractive.) but that's beside the point.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Leo's name came to me very easily. I had his nickname picked out before I had the rest of his name. (His surname didn't come to me until book two) I had to list all the possible names for Leo and decide which one I wanted.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Step Four: Inktober 2018","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h3"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Because this was my first project that I was doing that was stretching my creative juices I spent October taking the \"inktober\" prompts and writing something every single day. Usually it was a short scene. Once and  a while the scene went longer and became a chapter. But I used each daily prompt to write something new in this world. It was a lot of fun finding my way through. Not many of the snippets appeared in my first draft but it gave me a bunch of ideas.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Step Five: Draft One","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h3"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"1 November 2018","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I started the book!","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I was using my trial version of Scrivener. I had all of my Inktober prompts saved. I had pictures saved. I had all of my notes in one place. And I got started. As I wrote I sent each days' worth of writing to my friends. My maid of honor, my lifetime best friend, my husband. Around 1,667 words each day sent to them to read and let me know what they thought. And by the end of the month I had hit my 50,000 words goal. My story changed a lot in that one month in that first draft. And I immediately put it away and didn't look at it for years.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Fast Forward to December 2023","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"heading","version":1,"tag":"h1"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"My reading buddy and I were talking about books. I let slip that I had published a book in 2018 and had another one that had been sitting untouched for years. She left my home with her own copy of my novel and a digital copy of my first draft. Months later she came back to me with the best news. She had loved it. And she saw the potential in it. I set goals with her help and support. And months later I finished draft two. October 2024 I began inquiring after an agent and sent ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Pulchra","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" to an editor. Here we are in May 2025, 6.5 years after I wrote the first draft, working on the publishing path.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[],"direction":null,"format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":1,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"How ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":3,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Pulchra","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":1,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" Came to be:","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":1,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"1. Main Character","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"2. Conflict","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"3. Allies","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"4. Inktober","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"5. NaNoWriMo 2018","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"6. Re-read/draft 2 January 2019","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"7. Let it marinate on my laptop","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"8. Lost the ending in a computer transfer in 2020","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"9. Finish a basic ending 2020","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"10. Give to Sabrina in December 2023","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"11. Finish draft August 2024","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"(Start drafting book 2)","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":2,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"12. Query agents October 2024","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"13. Begin self publishing process May 2025","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"14. PUBLISH AUGUST 2025","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":2,"textStyle":""}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"root","version":1}},"relatedPosts":[{"id":15,"title":"Where Do I Start?","categories":[8,9,7],"meta":{"image":28,"description":"I was asked where he should start with his book. I realized I don't remember where I started. I thought it was worth it to write what I told him."},"slug":"where-do-i-start"}],"categories":["$6:props:children:3:props:children:props:children:props:children:0:props:children:props:doc:categories:2",{"id":10,"title":"Novel Updates","parent":null,"breadcrumbs":[{"id":"6792621a0c90a70a5c272169","doc":10,"url":null,"label":"Novel Updates"}],"updatedAt":"2025-01-23T15:36:58.312Z","createdAt":"2025-01-23T15:36:58.294Z"},"$6:props:children:3:props:children:props:children:props:children:0:props:children:props:doc:categories:0"],"meta":{"title":"My Inspiration Behind PULCHRA ARCANUM (the novel) ","image":{"id":29,"alt":"Original Pulchra Arcanum Cover (2018): Young girl looking at the viewer through leaves, bottom right hand corner reads Pulchra Arcanum by Mandy_Rose","caption":null,"updatedAt":"2025-04-22T19:12:13.705Z","createdAt":"2025-04-22T19:12:13.705Z","url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/download-1.jpg","thumbnailURL":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/download-1-300x450.jpg","filename":"download-1.jpg","mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":125952,"width":736,"height":1104,"focalX":50,"focalY":50,"sizes":{"thumbnail":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/download-1-300x450.jpg","width":300,"height":450,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":25733,"filename":"download-1-300x450.jpg"},"square":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/download-1-500x500.jpg","width":500,"height":500,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":47289,"filename":"download-1-500x500.jpg"},"small":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/download-1-600x900.jpg","width":600,"height":900,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":87321,"filename":"download-1-600x900.jpg"},"medium":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/download-1-900x1350.jpg","width":900,"height":1350,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":165972,"filename":"download-1-900x1350.jpg"},"large":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/download-1-1400x2100.jpg","width":1400,"height":2100,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":310024,"filename":"download-1-1400x2100.jpg"},"xlarge":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/download-1-1920x2880.jpg","width":1920,"height":2880,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":475214,"filename":"download-1-1920x2880.jpg"}}},"description":"My process to get my first draft of Pulchra Arcanum had a lot more than I realized when I started the process. Here's the breakdown!"},"publishedAt":"2025-05-01T17:00:00.000Z","authors":[3],"populatedAuthors":[{"id":3,"name":"Mandy"}],"slug":"inspiration-behind-pulchra-arcanum","slugLock":true,"updatedAt":"2025-05-01T17:14:57.939Z","createdAt":"2025-01-23T15:35:43.514Z","_status":"published"},"relationTo":"posts","showCategories":true}]}],["$","div","3",{"className":"col-span-4","children":["$","$L17",null,{"className":"h-full","doc":{"id":10,"title":"My World of Glass Inspiration","content":{"root":{"children":[{"children":[],"direction":null,"format":"center","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"format":"","type":"block","version":2,"fields":{"id":"67b75de8099a9c40b380e454","style":"success","content":{"root":{"children":[{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"“Saying a flood of lights filled the room would have been an exaggeration, but there was lighter than I’d seen in quite a while. A flurry of words sounded and I could identify three or four different voices. “Hey, you can all ask your questions in a minute, but right now I have someone to introduce you to...","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"— Demetri Kirk, My World of Glass","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"center","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"root","version":1}},"blockName":"","blockType":"banner"}},{"children":[],"direction":null,"format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"The most common question authors receive is where they receive inspiration for their stories. My own mother often tells me \"I just can't believe these books are inside your head.\" I share the inspiration for My World of Glass often, but here it is for the blog:","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"The idea for ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"My World of Glass","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" came from nothing else than, wait for it, brushing my teeth. I remember one night getting ready for bed, during Christmas break, and I was brushing my teeth. I had finished working on another project that night and had been telling my best friend about the progress when Dessa walked into my mind.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Not only did she walk in, but she had Demetri with her. I knew their names. I knew what they looked like. I even could see the cement bunker they seemed to walk into. I heard Demetri tell Dessa, “Meet the Crew.” I heard him introduce each of them. Harvey, Bastien, Celina (who later became Celia) and Timber, Laura Lee and Amber, and Jeremy. I could see them all. I knew what made them tick. (I knew Harvey had a secret, and I knew what it meant for Dessa, but didn’t know what the secret was.) I didn’t know what they were doing in the bunker. I didn’t know why Dessa’s back hurt the way it did.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I remember running to my phone (toothbrush still in my mouth) and immediately texting my best friend “I JUST HAD THE GREATEST IDEA”. Of course, she thought I was talking about the book I was already working on. I instantly grabbed a paper and wrote down every detail I could think of and sent a picture of it to her. She instantly fell in love with Demetri (who wouldn’t?) and insisted I work on it.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"The next day I wrote the entire scene (now in chapter three) and then started from the beginning. Within the very first scene I knew exactly what the title was. I knew why Dessa was in so much pain. I felt so much sympathy for this girl. I ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"needed","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" to tell her story. From the very beginning I knew I wasn’t writing this story for myself, I was writing it for someone else; for everyone else. ","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"This book went through so many (six!) drafts. I cried over it, I got angry about it, I defended it like I would a child. It was amazing, it was terrible, it was everything to me. I started this story before I even had a diagnosis for what was going on in my life. Nothing about it related to my life, other than the pesky nightmares (so I thought). But after I was diagnosed with PTSD I recognized the symptoms Dessa had as well. It allowed me to go back in my first rewrite and explain, in depth, what was going on with me ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"and","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" Dessa. It allowed me to explain things I didn’t know I needed to explain. Dessa became my best friend in some ways, we helped each other.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"When Demetri threw in the plot twist he did I remember staring at my computer, screaming, and asking my mom for the car keys. I drove straight to my best friend’s house, threw myself on her bed, and told her all about how her favorite character was making my life hard. I, the author, had been thrown a curve ball I did not appreciate.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Writing ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"My World of Glass","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" was an adventure. I loved every minute of writing it, rewriting it, falling in love with it, hating it. But I always knew I needed this book to be published. I’ll talk more about that another post, but I always thought I would “Traditionally” publish this book. I spent two ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"years","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" trying. In October, a month after I got married, I knew it was time. I had to publish this book. I threw 7 more offers out into the universe and when I still got no answer, I decided Independent publishing was the way I needed to go.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I look forward to sharing more secrets and behind the scene looks with you. Stay tuned! Subscribe! Know that if there is ever anything you want to see talked about on here I am all for it. ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":1,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"If I can’t find the answer, I’ll spotlight someone who can.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"root","version":1}},"relatedPosts":[{"id":4,"title":"Introductions","categories":[7],"meta":{"image":8,"description":"I write for an audience. It's what motivates me. I want to have conversations with my readers!  I am so glad you're here."},"slug":"introductions"}],"categories":["$6:props:children:3:props:children:props:children:props:children:0:props:children:props:doc:categories:2"],"meta":{"title":"The inspiration behind the novel My World of Glass","image":{"id":21,"alt":"Book cover for My World of Glass showing a landscape image with cracked glass in front of it","caption":null,"updatedAt":"2025-02-20T16:58:14.767Z","createdAt":"2025-02-20T16:58:14.767Z","url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/My World of Glass cover.jpg","thumbnailURL":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/My World of Glass cover-300x483.jpg","filename":"My World of Glass cover.jpg","mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":190091,"width":750,"height":1207,"focalX":50,"focalY":50,"sizes":{"thumbnail":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/My World of Glass cover-300x483.jpg","width":300,"height":483,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":38286,"filename":"My World of Glass cover-300x483.jpg"},"square":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/My World of Glass cover-500x500.jpg","width":500,"height":500,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":62230,"filename":"My World of Glass cover-500x500.jpg"},"small":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/My World of Glass cover-600x966.jpg","width":600,"height":966,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":120165,"filename":"My World of Glass cover-600x966.jpg"},"medium":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/My World of Glass cover-900x1448.jpg","width":900,"height":1448,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":220079,"filename":"My World of Glass cover-900x1448.jpg"},"large":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/My World of Glass cover-1400x2253.jpg","width":1400,"height":2253,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":405340,"filename":"My World of Glass cover-1400x2253.jpg"},"xlarge":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/My World of Glass cover-1920x3090.jpg","width":1920,"height":3090,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":616065,"filename":"My World of Glass cover-1920x3090.jpg"}}},"description":"The most common question I receive is where I receive inspiration for my stories. I share the story behind My World of Glass often, so here it is."},"publishedAt":"2025-02-20T17:00:00.000Z","authors":[3],"populatedAuthors":[{"id":3,"name":"Mandy"}],"slug":"my-world-of-glass-inspiration","slugLock":true,"updatedAt":"2025-02-20T16:59:26.898Z","createdAt":"2025-01-23T15:35:32.243Z","_status":"published"},"relationTo":"posts","showCategories":true}]}],["$","div","4",{"className":"col-span-4","children":["$","$L17",null,{"className":"h-full","doc":{"id":9,"title":"What's a Pantser? Where do I begin?","content":{"root":{"children":[{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Today I decided to write a little bit about how I begin writing a new story. Every author is different, so take what I say with a grain of salt. If what I suggest doesn’t work for you, find your own path and you do you! This is absolutely not a one-size-fits-all deal. Every book (even within the same genres!) are all different because the authors are all different.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Now, into the good stuff.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I used to be a “pantser” (aka, someone who just sits down and starts writing by the seat of their pants.) This kind of author doesn’t know what’ll happen next. They don’t have any plans for the future, they let the characters tell their story. It’s an incredibly exciting and rewarding way to write stories and bravo to those authors! I loved writing like this because it made me feel adventurous and like I was on the ride, alongside my characters. (My Rose Winters novellas were both pantsed novels. Stephen King also reportedly pantses his stories.)","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Nothing short of immense awe goes to those authors who are “planners” either. These are the authors who, well, plan their story. They have varying levels of detail for themselves. Some planning authors plan every little character arc, every plot detail, everything short of the actual conversations. (though some do throw in ideas of what scenes could be, by including dialogue or scenery or what have you.) These are the authors you picture with the “idea wall” and sticky notes everywhere. JK Rowling and EL Stein both admit to being planners. (We can totally see the crazy detail oriented Planner JKR is by her entire Pottermore website having crazy amounts of detail you would never even think of. Like the bathroom announcement. Don’t ask.)","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"With my last several projects I have become a mix of these two, a “plantser” if you will. I have the general idea of my story and what is supposed to happen. But I am still that person texting my best friend near tears and saying, “my character is doing something I don’t like!” and completely changing the rest of my outline from there. For the purpose of this post I’m going to talk about my Nanowrimo 2018 experience. I hadn’t “won” a Nano in 4 years. (When I say win I mean reaching 50,000 words in a novel in 30 days.) I was determined to win that year because I wanted the discount code to Scrivener, a program I use to this day.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"For 2018 I started with the basics. I had an idea (I wanted to write a story about Merlin, King Arthur, and a secret.) I started by naming my characters. Merlin and Arthur were obvious. But I went to ","type":"text","version":1},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"my favorite naming website","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"link","version":3,"fields":{"doc":null,"linkType":"custom","newTab":true,"url":"https://www.behindthename.com/"},"id":"67b766e1099a9c40b380e45b"},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" and started looking up other medieval names that I liked. I sent a list of them to some friends to narrow down and came to two different names. With those two names I had two different plots my story could take. I decided to merge the two, choose my favorite name, and go from there. I finished naming all of the characters I needed to. Then I went and found the ","type":"text","version":1},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Save the Cat Beat Sheet ","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"link","version":3,"fields":{"doc":null,"linkType":"custom","newTab":true,"url":"https://timstout.wordpress.com/story-structure/blake-snyders-beat-sheet/"},"id":"67b766e1099a9c40b380e45c"},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"which I love dearly for planning. (This link leads you to explanations of each beat.)","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Once I got an idea of what each “beat” would mean, I sat back and looked at what I had created. I knew who my main characters were, what makes them tick, and even found pictures on Pinterest to represent who each of my characters would be. (Merlin was represented by a nice picture of Harrison Ford, my female main character’s mother played by Blake Lively.) I even had a friend model for me so I could make a temporary cover for my book for the competition.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Once I had all of that done, I still, regrettably, had about a month until Nanowrimo. But I felt like I wanted to get to know my characters a little bit more. I found a copy of 2018’s “inktober” prompts. These prompts are meant for artists, not writers. But it still worked. Each day of October you were given a single word as a prompt. Artists use this prompt in order to spread their talents and learn to do new art they wouldn’t normally do, or challenge themselves in their own medium and style. I took each of those words and every day would write a scene or a paragraph based on that word. Some days were super easy, others were a bit of a challenge. And one in particular (whale) I straight up had no idea how to incorporate. It was a fun way to learn who my characters were and how they acted. Only a few of those scenes ended up in my novel by the end of November. The rest of them were just fun to imagine side conversations.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"By the time I sat down to write my story I had my cast of characters, my plot structure, and several scenes to help me get started. Despite this, my ending ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"did","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" change by the time I was done with the first draft. (Characters still have control over their story in my process a wee bit.) I ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"did","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" have a side character who surprised me. And that is where I get to enjoy the pantsing part of my story. I enjoy letting the characters take the wheel. Even if it throws me off and put me behind a few days in the competition. I ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"still made it","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":".  Now, 7 years later, my ending still looks worlds different and the editing process has sometimes felt overwhelming. But the fact is - I wrote a 50,000 word (about 140 pages in A5 size) first draft in 30 days.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"That project was ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Pulchra Arcanum","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" and the first book of 3 will be (hopefully) releasing later this year. Subscribe to my newsletter and (or) follow me on social media for updates!","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"As always, if there is a question I didn’t answer, let me know! I would love to answer it for you yourself, and then also add in an article talking about it.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"start","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"root","version":1}},"relatedPosts":["$6:props:children:3:props:children:props:children:props:children:3:props:children:props:doc:relatedPosts:0"],"categories":["$6:props:children:3:props:children:props:children:props:children:0:props:children:props:doc:categories:0","$6:props:children:3:props:children:props:children:props:children:0:props:children:props:doc:categories:2","$6:props:children:3:props:children:props:children:props:children:2:props:children:props:doc:categories:1","$6:props:children:3:props:children:props:children:props:children:0:props:children:props:doc:categories:1"],"meta":{"title":"What's a pantser and where do I begin when writing a novel?","image":{"id":25,"alt":"A blue door set into a wall of old fashioned and vintage books","caption":null,"updatedAt":"2025-02-20T17:40:36.730Z","createdAt":"2025-02-20T17:40:36.730Z","url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/book wall.jpg","thumbnailURL":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/book wall-300x190.jpg","filename":"book wall.jpg","mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":89489,"width":640,"height":406,"focalX":50,"focalY":50,"sizes":{"thumbnail":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/book wall-300x190.jpg","width":300,"height":190,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":23688,"filename":"book wall-300x190.jpg"},"square":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/book wall-500x500.jpg","width":500,"height":500,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":72329,"filename":"book wall-500x500.jpg"},"small":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/book wall-600x381.jpg","width":600,"height":381,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":78147,"filename":"book wall-600x381.jpg"},"medium":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/book wall-900x571.jpg","width":900,"height":571,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":138984,"filename":"book wall-900x571.jpg"},"large":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/book wall-1400x888.jpg","width":1400,"height":888,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":251805,"filename":"book wall-1400x888.jpg"},"xlarge":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/book wall-1920x1218.jpg","width":1920,"height":1218,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":380113,"filename":"book wall-1920x1218.jpg"}}},"description":"Pantser? Planner? Plantser? What are these terms and how do they relate to starting a fictional novel? In this post I talk about my general process."},"publishedAt":"2025-03-30T18:15:00.000Z","authors":[3],"populatedAuthors":[{"id":3,"name":"Mandy"}],"slug":"whats-a-pantser-where-do-i-begin","slugLock":true,"updatedAt":"2025-03-30T18:13:00.741Z","createdAt":"2025-01-23T15:35:09.181Z","_status":"published"},"relationTo":"posts","showCategories":true}]}],["$","div","5",{"className":"col-span-4","children":["$","$L17",null,{"className":"h-full","doc":{"id":4,"title":"Introductions","content":{"root":{"children":[{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Hello! I don't normally like talking about myself, but for some reason it is so much easier to introduce myself to strangers. So, even though I may already know some of you, I'm going to pretend I don't for a moment.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Starting from the beginning. I have been writing ever since my mom showed me I could staple papers together to make a book. Fast forward and I'm in an after school writing club in middle school. From that class I'll publish my two novellas and begin writing full length novels. The first of which will be published in 2018, ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"My World of Glass","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":".","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Away from writing, I live in Utah with my dream man (quite literally - I found 14 year old Me's \"wish list\" and he tics off all the requirements) and our daughter and our tri-colored corgi and yellow lab. I have a degree in criminal justice which accompanies my newest degree in social work, and I work in my dream job in child welfare. Basically, I've made it in life.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"However, I'm not even 30 yet so I have a lot to keep working toward. Part of that goal is to publish more of my stories. I'm not one of those authors who is terrified of having people read their work. I would MUCH rather have people read it and tell me it wasn't for them. I write for an audience. It's what motivates me. So in order to keep my fantasy escape, I have to keep writing and keep sharing.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"If you've followed me for a while you'll know occasionally I drop random musings. But I try to keep my posts relevant. Please ask me questions and please let me know what kind of content you would like to see. I want to have conversations with my readers! Thank you for joining me on my journey, I am so glad you're here.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"root","version":1}},"relatedPosts":[],"categories":["$6:props:children:3:props:children:props:children:props:children:0:props:children:props:doc:categories:2"],"meta":{"title":"Introducing - Mandy Tremelling | Behind the Scenes","image":{"id":8,"alt":"The letters MT in a gold flowy font with intricate details in the background including a dragon and a pen with a dagger hilt.","caption":null,"updatedAt":"2025-01-23T18:31:04.710Z","createdAt":"2025-01-23T18:31:04.710Z","url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e.jpg","thumbnailURL":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-300x266.jpg","filename":"8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e.jpg","mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":49791,"width":667,"height":591,"focalX":50,"focalY":50,"sizes":{"thumbnail":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-300x266.jpg","width":300,"height":266,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":15266,"filename":"8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-300x266.jpg"},"square":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-500x500.jpg","width":500,"height":500,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":37265,"filename":"8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-500x500.jpg"},"small":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-600x532.jpg","width":600,"height":532,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":41142,"filename":"8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-600x532.jpg"},"medium":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-900x797.jpg","width":900,"height":797,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":69634,"filename":"8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-900x797.jpg"},"large":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-1400x1240.jpg","width":1400,"height":1240,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":126678,"filename":"8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-1400x1240.jpg"},"xlarge":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-1920x1701.jpg","width":1920,"height":1701,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":194244,"filename":"8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-1920x1701.jpg"}}},"description":"I write for an audience. It's what motivates me. I want to have conversations with my readers!  I am so glad you're here."},"publishedAt":"2025-01-22T22:00:00.000Z","authors":[3],"populatedAuthors":[{"id":3,"name":"Mandy"}],"slug":"introductions","slugLock":true,"updatedAt":"2025-01-23T18:31:06.899Z","createdAt":"2025-01-22T21:08:51.230Z","_status":"published"},"relationTo":"posts","showCategories":true}]}]]}]}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"container","children":false}]]}]
1a:I[86700,["4839","static/chunks/4839-6dc9841672373a02.js","6622","static/chunks/6622-1b4d460dc484ce49.js","8088","static/chunks/8088-06a674efe926cc48.js","9122","static/chunks/9122-398c7b093684fef1.js","9559","static/chunks/app/(frontend)/layout-3a597292563e832a.js"],"HeaderClient"]
